  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="pr_propsofcong"></xref></title>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>n</m> be a natural number and let <m>a,
        b, c, \text{ and }   d</m> be integers.
        We assume that <m>a \equiv b \pmod n</m> and
        <m>c \equiv d \pmod n</m> and will prove that <m>\mod{(a + c)}{(b + d)}{n}</m>.
        Since <m>\mod{a}{b}{n}</m> and <m>\mod{c}{d}{n}</m>,
        <m>n</m> divides <m>(a - b)</m> and <m>(c - d)</m> and so there exist integers <m>k</m> and <m>q</m> such that
        <m>a - b = nk</m> and <m>c - d = nq</m>.
        We can then write <m>a = b + nk</m> and <m>c = d + nq</m> and obtain
        <md>
          <mrow>a + c \amp = (b + nk) + (d + nq)</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = (b + d) + n(k + q)</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        By subtracting <m>(b + d)</m> from both sides of the last equation,
        we see that
        <me>
          (a + c) - (b + d) = n(k + q)
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>(k + q)</m> is an integer,
        this proves that <m>n</m> divides <m>(a + c) - (b + d)</m>,
        and hence,
        we can conclude that <m>\mod{(a + c)}{(b + d)}{n}</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title><xref ref="prog_propertiesofcong"></xref></title>
    <p>
      <em>Case 2</em>.
      <m>\left( \mod{a}{2}{5} \right)</m>.
      In this case,
      we use <xref ref="T_propsofcong">Theorem</xref> to conclude that
      <me>
        \mod{a^2}{2^2}{5}  \text{ or }   \mod{a^2}{4}{5}
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This proves that if <m>\mod{a}{2}{5}</m>,
      then <m>\mod{a^2}{4}{5}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Case 3</em>.
      <m>\left( \mod{a}{3}{5} \right)</m>.
      In this case,
      we use <xref ref="T_propsofcong">Theorem</xref> to conclude that
      <me>
        \mod{a^2}{3^2}{5}  \text{ or }   \mod{a^2}{9}{5}
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We also know that <m>\mod{9}{4}{5}</m>.
      So we have <m>\mod{a^2}{9}{5}</m> and <m>\mod{9}{4}{5}</m>,
      and we can now use the transitive property of congruence
      (<xref ref="T_modprops">Theorem</xref>)
      to conclude that <m>\mod{a^2}{4}{5}</m>.
      This proves that if <m>\mod{a}{3}{5}</m>,
      then <m>\mod{a^2}{4}{5}</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
